 The Windimurra Project covers rocks of the Windimurra and Narndee Complexes, which are large 
 mafic  intrusions close to a flexure and fault intersection on the archon-archon domain boundary 
 separating  the  Murchison  and  Southern  Cross  Domains.  They  have  been  interpreted  as  large, 
 layered  intrusions  of  gabbro,  anorthosite,  pyroxenite,  peridotite  and  magnetic  cumulates.  The 
 Windimurra Complex has a total outcrop area of 2,120 km2 and comprises hundreds of rhythmic 
 layers  of  gabbro,  dolerite,  gabbronorite,  anorthosite,  pyroxenite  and  magnetite  cumulates.  The 
 Narndee  Complex  sits  to  the  south  of  the  Windimurra,  and  consists  predominantly  of  repeated 
 cycles of peridotite/pyroxenite through to gabbro and gabbronorite.  
 For both complexes, a minimum Rb-Sr age date of 2669Ma has been constrained by felsic dykes 
 cutting  the  mafic  rocks,  with  a  Sm-Nd  age  date  of  2800Ma  recently  calculated.  The  complexes 
 have been intruded by granites, pegmatites and porphyritic dykes.  
 There is very little encouragement in either the aeromagnetics and/or the geochemistry that there 
 are  prospective  ultramafic  rocks  in  the  area  relinquished.  Outcrop  in  the  relinquished  portion  is 
 scarce, however granitic rocks have been mapped and interpreted as underlying much of the area. 
 The Windimurra Complex outcrops as gabbros in the north-east corner of the relinquished area. 
 Figure  3  shows  the  GSWA  mapped  geology  of  the  area,  topography  and  the  area  to  be 
 relinquished shaded blue.

 Geochemistry 
 In  2004,  a  lag  sampling  geochemical  program  was  undertaken  on  leases  in  the  Windimurrra 
 Project area. Deflation lag samples (-6 + 2mm) were taken in areas of good lag, with magnetic lags 
 taken  where  the  lag  sampling  medium  was  poor.  A  total  of  31  samples  were  taken  from  the 
 relinquished  portion  of  the  lease  near  Boodanoo,  comprising  29  magnetic  lag  samples  and  2 
 deflation  lag  samples.  These  samples  were  analysed  for  (ppm  detection  limit  in  brackets)  by 
 ICP-MS:  As(0.5),  Ag(0.5),  Au(0.001),  Bi(0.1),  Cd(0.5),  Mo(0.2),  Pb(1),  Pt(0.0005),  Pd(0.0005), 
 Sb(0.2), U(0.1) and ICP-OES: Ca(10), Co(2), Cr(5), Cu(2), Fe(10), Mg(10), Mn(1), Ni(1),  Ti(10), 
 V(2), Zn(1). The results are included in Appendix 3 and sample locations are depicted in Figure 7. 
 Most of the samples were taken at a spacing of 500m x 200m, with a small area of 250m x 100m 
 to cope with limitations of the granted lease area. The maximum nickel returned in the relinquished 
 area was 42ppm (with 24ppm Cu, 36.6% Fe). There were no geochemical anomalies in the area 
 sampled. The majority of the area to be relinquished is associated with salt lakes, and geochemical 
 sampling was not carried as it was decided that it would not be effective. 
 CONCLUSIONS AND RECOMMENDATIONS 
 The  Narndee  and  Windimurra  Intrusive  complexes  have  been  interpreted  as  large,  layered 
 intrusions of gabbro, anorthosite, pyroxenite, peridotite and magnetic cumulates. The Narndee and 
 Mulyeron Hill areas are interpreted as having greater potential for nickel sulphide mineralisation. 
 The  area  to  be  relinquished does not appear to contain prospective ground for the discovery of 
 nickel sulphide or PGE mineralisation.
